properties.SPECIES COMMENTS: Lights phase. Harassed by crows. Stunning against the snow. Front of wing bright (including axillaries). Wrists had large dark spots. Hind wing covered in wide dark band from tip to body. Rump milk white.

Dark morph; large buteo flying upriver over Scovell Island away from a group of crows. Bicolor wing pattern, looking like a “t” the color of dark chocolate from underneath with white on posterior side of underwing. Distinct black wingtips. Some white on the tail with a thick dark band at the end. After much deliberation several factors led us to rule out a dark morph Harlan’s red-tailed hawk. We saw no distinct long barring on underside of primary feathers, and noticed a longer and somewhat thinner looking tail with no distinct wing bulge creating a different silhouette than RTHA. Flight pattern also was not rigid and crow-like as RTHA, more similar to a harrier with shorter almost oval wingbeats.

We saw no distinct long barring on underside of primary feathers, and noticed a longer and somewhat thinner looking tail with no distinct wing bulge creating a different silhouette than RTHA. Flight pattern also was not rigid and crow-like as RTHA, more similar to a harrier with shorter almost oval wingbeats.

We saw no distinct long barring on underside of primary feathers, and noticed a longer and somewhat thinner looking tail with no distinct wing bulge creating a different silhouette than RTHA. Flight pattern also was not rigid and crow-like as RTHA, more similar to a harrier with shorter almost oval wingbeats.

Two Rough-legged Hawks observed for 5 minutes with binoculars and a spotting scope as they flew in the same area. After 5 minutes one flew eastward, and we observed the remaining one for another 5 minutes before it flew out of sight beyond some trees near the top of a small hill. Easy to identify with binoculars and scope, but too far for photos. ----They were seen over snow-covered, open farmland. The snow on the ground reflected a lot of light which lit up them up very well, and we immediately ruled out they were Red-tailed or Red-shouldered Hawks. ----While soaring, the wings had a low dihedral, and slow wingbeats when not soaring. The underside of the wings showed the dark carpal squares, dark wingtips, dark underwing coverts, and wide terminal band on the tail. Their face masks were also easy to see.

properties.SPECIES COMMENTS: continuing birds; see photo that shows both male and female together (based on plumage differences). There was a case where a Red-tailed Hawk swooped down to the ground and one of the Rough-legged Hawks came and hovered over it before flying off. Otherwise, the sky was crowded with the four Hawks, two Ravens, and one Killdeer who flew up and mobbed the low-flying Red-tail for a few seconds. Lots of wind today allowed for easy soaring and hovering flight by the hawks.
